
On any given morning, dozens of men, some wearing work clothes covered with splotches of paint and wall compound, gather at Northwood Drive and Roswell Road &mdash; the gateway to Sandy Springs. Many came here from places such as Mexico, Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador &mdash; drawn by the same opportunities that have called immigrants to America for decades: freedom and economic opportunity. But as they stand on the street corners of this new city, they represent not only the latest wave of people seeking the American dream but also a minefield of problems for local residents and businesses. 

